  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Adessium Foundation- No Nukes</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The cooperation with Adessium over the years has allowed PAX to resume national and global leadership on the nuclear weapons issue. These efforts to build and strengthen norms require ongoing attention, and this cooperation has been invaluable in providing the scope and space to allow for flexible approaches to build to a new norm. The overall purpose of this project is to start, and conclude, negotiations on a new legally binding instrument prohibiting nuclear weapons leading to their elimination. Recognising that elimination follows prohibition, a new treaty banning nuclear weapons negotiated in the near term, is the best way to move closer towards nuclear abolition. In the years of cooperation with Adessium, PAX has been a the forefront of the movement leading to the ban. In 2010 PAX&#x2019;s efforts to bring attention to the contradictions and legal loopholes in the non-proliferation treaty contributed to the establishment of an action plan that included both reference to the humanitarian consequences of any use of nuclear weapons, international humanitarian law and the need to remove nuclear weapons from security strategies and doctrines. The research conduced in 2010 and 2011, and the presentation of a nuclear free view of security for NATO brought PAX (then IKV Pax Christi) to the attention of key countries as a significant contributor to the security and nuclear weapons discourse. PAX, working with partners including the Rode Kruis and ASN Bank, achieved the only public commitment by a NATO member state to participate in the ban treaty negotiations. The Teken Tegen Kernwapens campaign, building on years of intensive parliamentary education and advocacy, resulted in a clear and unambiguous majority of political parties telling the Dutch government it should actively support a nuclear ban treaty.</narrative>
  </description>
